The issue in this line of code is that you are trying to assign a single `GameObject` instance to an array of `GameObject[]`. 

To fix this issue, you need to initialize the array with a specific size, and then assign individual `GameObject` instances to the elements of the array.

Here's an example:

```
GameObject[] foodProjectile = new GameObject[size];
```

Replace `size` with the desired size of the array. After initializing the array, you can assign individual `GameObject` instances to the elements of the array using indexes, like this:

```
foodProjectile[0] = new GameObject();
foodProjectile[1] = new GameObject();
// ...
```

Alternatively, if you want to initialize the array with a specific set of `GameObject` instances, you can do it like this:

```
GameObject[] foodProjectile = new GameObject[]
{
    new GameObject(),
    new GameObject(),
    // ...
};
```

Replace `new GameObject()` with the desired `GameObject` instances that you want to assign to the array elements.

To get the size or number of elements in a `List<GameObject>`, you can use the `Count` property.

Here's an example:

```csharp
List<GameObject> foodProjectiles = new List<GameObject>();
// Add elements to the list

int size = foodProjectiles.Count;
```

In the above code, `foodProjectiles.Count` will give you the number of elements currently present in the `List<GameObject>`.
